      <hedline>
        <hl1>No State Income Tax for Teachers? Not So Fast</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Sheila Feit says rather than offer teachers exemption from state income tax, as Gov Gray Davis of California has proposed, offer college tuition costs for teachers who agree to teach in areas with shortages, as Gov Goerge E Pataki of New York did</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Gov. Gray Davis's offer of an exemption from the state income tax for teachers in California (front page, May 14) seems ill advised. Experienced teachers in that state earn $50,000 a year on average.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Gov. Gray Davis's offer of an exemption from the state income tax for teachers in California (front page, May 14) seems ill advised. Experienced teachers in that state earn $50,000 a year on average.</p>
        <p>Better to offer, as Gov. George E. Pataki did, college tuition costs for those who agree to teach in areas with shortages.</p>
        <p>Or, tax or voucher credits could be offered to low-income parents, allowing them real choices for their children.</p>
        <p>SHEILA FEIT  Syosset, N.Y., May 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
